            "id": "1606718fa0da41e98ff07",
            "questionText": "A biomedical researcher needs to precisely measure the diameter of a microscopic fiber. They use a micrometer screw gauge. Before measuring, they check for zero error by closing the jaws and find that the main scale reading is $!$0.00\\,mm$!$ and the thimble scale reading is $!$3$!$ divisions above the datum line, with each thimble division representing $!$0.01\\,mm$!$. This indicates a positive zero error. When measuring the fiber, the main scale shows $!$0.5\\,mm$!$ and the thimble scale aligns at $!$15$!$ divisions. They ensure their eye is directly perpendicular to the scale to avoid parallax error. Calculate the actual diameter of the fiber in nanometres ($!$nm$!$), expressing the final value in standard notation.",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "42d44784594f41b49daf3",
                    "stepText": "Let's start by identifying the method to compute the zero error from the micrometer reading when the jaws are closed. Please choose the expression that correctly relates the number of thimble divisions and the value per division.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "9a4da118-2c7f-416d-9990-5c7e8ca6e378"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$3 \\times 0.01\\,mm$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$0.01 + 3\\,mm$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$3 \\div 0.01\\,mm$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "742ffe8e371643178ae20",
                    "stepText": "Great, now calculate the zero error by multiplying the number of divisions by the value per division.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "0.03"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "mm",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "9a4da118-2c7f-416d-9990-5c7e8ca6e378"
                    ],
                    "options": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "c0da23a38c7c4249a4e21",
                    "stepText": "Next, let's identify the correct expression for obtaining the total measurement reading from the micrometer when measuring the fiber. Which formula correctly sums the main scale reading and the contribution from the thimble scale?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$0.5\\,mm + (15 \\times 0.01\\,mm)$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$15\\,mm + (0.5 \\div 0.01\\,mm)$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$0.5\\,mm \\times (15 \\times 0.01\\,mm)$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "24c98e85c9bb421c86ff0",
                    "stepText": "Now, compute the total measured reading by adding the main scale value to the product of the thimble divisions and the division value.",
                    "stepText2": "",
